{
  "answer": "**Manu and Yājñavalkya on the Brahmin's Authority**\n\nIn the *Manusmṛti*, the Brahmin's superiority is rooted both in divine origin—emerging from the Creator's mouth—and in the role of safeguarding Vedic knowledge, making the priestly class inherently lordly.[^1] Likewise, the *Yājñavalkya Smṛti* describes Brahmins as created by Brahmā specifically to protect the Vedas and uphold *dharma*, emphasizing their custodial authority over sacred tradition.[^2]\n\n**Cynewulf on Priests' Authority**\n\nCynewulf's poems (*Andreas*, *Elene*, *Juliana*) do not contain passages explicitly grounding priests' authority in speaking \"from inside Christ's body\" (a likely reference to the Church as the mystical Body of Christ, per Pauline theology). While the works abound with references to Christ, the Church, and holy figures (e.g., apostles, bishops), no direct discussion of priests (*preost*) or their ecclesial authority appears in the English translations. Searches for related concepts (\"priest,\" \"preost,\" \"body of Christ,\" \"Christ's body\") yielded no matches in Cynewulf's corpus. The poems focus on saints' martyrdoms and visions rather than clerical office.\n\n**Comparison: Which is Harder for an Outsider to Assume?**\n\nThe Brahmin role is harder for an outsider to assume. Birth as a Brahmin is an immutable divine precondition, predetermining authority alongside (but secondary to) Vedic mastery—non-Brahmins cannot ritually teach or officiate.[^3] Cynewulf's Christian priesthood, if tied to ecclesial membership (\"inside Christ's body\"), requires only baptism and ordination, accessible to converts regardless of origin (e.g., Gentiles in apostolic missions). No birth-barrier exists, making it far easier for outsiders.\n\n[^1]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-7c0113).\n\n[^2]: *Yājñavalkya Smṛti*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-yajnavalkya-smrti-cb88d6/01/translation/#p-f37a48).\n\n[^3]: *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 1, [paragraphs](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/01/translation/#p-7c0113) (birth and Veda as basis); cf. Chapter 10 for *varṇa* duties excluding outsiders from Brahmin roles.",
